...Upier is just one of many forms of word from many Slavic languages which means vampire/undead. In Polish most popular form is upiór ("ó" you read like "u". We have 2 letters for one sound, dont ask me why :). 
You can read about it here: https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/upi%C3%B3r  and here:   https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Reconstruction:Proto-Slavic/%C7%ABpyr%D1%8C   
I really appreciate translators hard work, but it would be nice if they would change her name to proper spelling. Just call her Upiór or Upir or Upier, or something like that :) Is there any way to contact translators?

Haha. Her name is not Yupiel xD 
She is Polish, so her "name" is word from Polish language, which was later writen in katakana to be later translated to English language. This is how this weird creation came to be :) There is no such name as Yupiel in Poland. Even more. There is no such word in Polish language which would start with "y" letter. Only foreign words can do it. In Polish, sound represented in English as letter "y" is represented by letter "j". But even when we will swap thse letters "Jupiel" does have no sence what so ever. It is because there should not be this "y" sound to begin with. This is just katakana "artifact :) 
Also everyone knows that in Japanese language there is no difference between "r" and "l" sound (obviously Im not an expert, but I think I am right about that. That is why we have all those "get leddy" in Japanese fighting games :) 
So knowing all this, if we will remove "y" from the beginning and will change "l" to "r" letter, we will get Upier...
